        <comment>
  <id>20280720</id>
  <body><![CDATA[I think they need to grow up a little before they decide it's time to commit to someone forever, and/or have sex. The thing with YA literature that tends to irritate the hell out of me is the fact that these kids seem to think the person they're currently into is their forever love, their soul mate. <br /><br />Books like the Hunger Games or The Demon's Covenant contain a realistic view of what went on in my head (relationship-view wise) when I was a teenager, so I can better relate to them, the characters in the books. I didn't run around thinking I was in love with every hot boy who gave me a smoldering look and could kiss like a pro. I loved the attention, sure, but I knew it wasn't "forever love". I never fooled myself into thinking that I met my soul mate during my teen years. <br /><br />I guess it's why I remained a virgin as a teenager, I'm cynical. Besides, romance never really was my thing. Well, and I grew up in a religious home. But still, plenty of other girls who were raised in my religion had sex during their teen years. I also know a lot of people raised without religion who chose to not have sex until they were really in love, and not the dramatic, hormone-fueled version of love one feels when they're teenagers. So, while religious beliefs can play a part it what teenagers choose to do or not do, I also KNOW that teenagers will do what they want. I'm not a fool.<br /><br />When it comes to sleeping around with little to no commitment, well I don't consider that empowering. I think it's sad, and depending on the circumstances, cheap. Call me old fashioned but I feel that when you have sex you're giving the most important part of yourself to your partner. Trusting them with everything you have to give. I think both parties should be emotionally ready to have sex. <br /><br />Heroes and Heroines don't always have to end up together. Love stories are great, but don't always have to be the end result of a story. <br /><br />I love books in which the heroine figures out who she is and solves her problems on her own, without relying on the "strong, smart man" to come along and solve all her problems. <br /><br />I want my girls to grow up knowing they're just as intelligent and capable as the boys their age. That romance isn't all that it's cracked up to be, and that you have to work at all relationships in order for them to work out. <br /><br />Also it must be said, I've never believed in the concept of soul mates or the whole "meant to be" thing (like I said, romance isn't really my thing, though I do believe in love). I don't believe in destiny. I believe that some people are better suited for eachother, and whether or not they get together is up to them. And whether or not their relationship works out is up to how much work they put into it.]]></body>
  
